Had a very good dinner here although the menu is limited. The bread is outstanding and a must order. They had a nice wine selection but limited liquor choices Noise level is high. Very good service. Very good deserts

A cute, modern pastry shop tucked in on a busy street corner. There is no sign out front, so we would've missed it if it weren't for the delicious smells wafting out from the shop. Highly recommend the morning bun. It looks like a cinnamon roll that is dusted with a beautiful layer of sugar and filled with orange zest. The orange zest is soo fragrant, and you can taste it with every bite. The bun itself is surprisingly dense but still crispy on the outside. The almond croissant had layers on layers of buttery flakiness and was dusted with powdered sugar. The inside was very soft and contained a delicious almond filling. Very dense and huge, so can easily be shared by two people.

The problem with me going to bakeries is that I tend to get too much and always shock myself at the register. Regardless, I never regret getting what I do. I would only regret not getting it to see how it tasted. In any case, this bakery always has a line but does move relatively quick. I think there was ~25 people ahead of me and I got to the register within 15 minutes. You pretty much order on your way to the register. Along the way I got: [1] Chocolate chip cookie ($4) - It's huge, flat and delicious. I didn't think about getting it but 2 groups that were ahead of me got one and so I figure why not! No regrets! I even picked up a bag near the register. [2] Canele ($4.25) - Expensive but this is probably one of the best ones I've had. The inside is more cakey then custardy like I'm use to but the zesty cake flavor was soooo good and the outside wasn't that bitter. If they have any I highly recommend it! [3] Gougere ($4.25) - It's like a hollow cheese bread. This was meh to me. It looked different on the inside compared to other pictures I've seen on yelp. [4] Frangipane Tart (~$8) - This was pretty good. I like the crust because it's very croissant like and the berries wasn't overly sweet. I think next time I will try the hazelnut one. I was just thrown off because the hazelnuts on top looked like corn nuts. [5] Baguette ($6) - Expensive as well but pretty good if you pair it with cheese. I prefer the softer baguettes like the ones you get with banh mi and at the Asian stores you can get them for a $1! I would have gotten a sandwich but I heard it takes about 15 minute to make. It feel very cramp and there's a fair amount of seating but not enough for my party. There's also outside seating but it was a cold day so I opted out of the sandwich. Maybe next time! I will definitely be back for the morning bun that I heard so much about and the pies looked amazing! So many good things to try and with such a small wallet I can only get so much.

Love, love, LOVE Tartine! Tartine and the sister Tartine Manufactory are always on my must visit list for San Francisco. What is not to love, okay there can be a wait if you don't plan accordingly, however while in line I have seen and met some very "interesting" characters and I'm sure the same can be said about me. The food is wonderful, freshly baked and the vibe is so San Francisco, I just love this place. So get up early walk, ride, taxi, or Uber and get your fill of great baked goods along with a tasty latte while watching the city life!

I am a long time customer here. However I will not be going here anymore because this place does not support its workers forming a union. Also in their Instagram page they are deleting comments by people calling them out for Union-busting, or they aren't allowing people to comment at all. Truly shameful. Their cofounder put out a letter to the public explaining why they are against the union, which I also find to be complete BS. If anything I am truly grateful they are showing their true colors. I will be taking my business elsewhere.

I've been baking w/ sourdough starter for over 3 years now and I've read Chad Robertson's Tartine Bread from cover to cover in just a few days. I've been wanting to visit this bakery for quite a long time. We had an awesome experience. Yes, there is a line, yes the ordering service is not necessarily convenient, yes it's hard to find a place to sit, but the quality that comes out of this place is unbeatable. We ordered 2 Plain Croissants, a Pain au Chocolat and one Morning Bun. Everything tasted out of this world and easily topped every I've ever had in their particular category, BY FAR! The croissants had an insane amount of layers, they were flaky and light, the gluten development in the interior of the croissant was just unbelievable - I had a hard time ripping it by just pulling it w/ my hands, and that's a good thing! This was hands down the best croissant I've ever had. Nothing I've had in France even comes close to this one. Another thing is the depth of flavor that I think comes from the fact that they use a mixture of sourdough starter and yeast to leaven them. Just fantastic, I encourage you try them plain! The morning bun was also a great choice with mind blowing textures. I had my doubts about the candied orange, but it totally works. The bun was tender enough w/ just the right amount of flakiness. It wasn't overwhelmingly sweet and I think it hit all the right notes. The Pain au Chocolat had this incredible rise to it. I don't think I've ever seen such a beautiful one in my life. The pastry itself was perfect and the chocolate inside was super high quality with an unbelievable melt. Usually you get this gritty crappy baking chocolate used by second class bakers that are afraid of it leaking out, not here. I also want to thank the staff for all the effort they put into everything - it really shows in the end product! I WILL be coming back, again and again and again and again.

I'm allergic to dairy (even small amounts of butter can't be used in cooking for me.) Luckily Tartine is known for their bread! I love the sesame bread here! it's just the perfect amount of chewy on the inside and crispy on the outside. I heard they're known for the country bread which is the classic sourdough. I've never tried it because it's always sold out by the time I get there in the afternoon on a weekday =( one day!! The staff told me all of their breads are soughdoughs though. It's just the other ones (like sesame) have a slight twist. You honestly can't go wrong with any of them :) Be careful! These are huge - but I doubt you'll have a hard time finding people to share tartine bread with.

Some say that Tartine's strength is in their breads and sweets, but I can only comment on the items that I've tried here. And in my opinion, the two items I tried were pricey and overhyped. Good: -Morning bun ($4.75) - good but not "the stuff of legends" good. The texture was thick and doughy, and they felt to me like a cross between a kouign amann and a cinnamon bun. It was good and not overly sweet but nothing mind-blowing. I wouldn't actively try to eat this again but would not be opposed if offered another one. Meh: -Croissant ($4.75) - this was quite expensive and disappointing. On the plus side, it was generously sized and extremely buttery in flavor. But they felt heavy to the touch, and the texture was too dense. They do look gorgeous though, with substantial, very browned crusts. It's also the price of most almond croissants elsewhere. Again, maybe their sourdough or tarts are better. But I didn't find the items I tried to be that great.

Your home made whipped cream is heavenly. This is very cozy place next to the beautiful Dolores Park with delicious brunches (including avocado roasts and delicious items ) and special organic bakeries & cakes. Healthy and yummy.

I almost missed this place since their signage is pretty much nonexistent on their storefront. Luckily, the line out the door let me know I arrived. Visited for the first time on Saturday around 4pm. Was worried that some of the pastries would be sold out but they still had everything I was eying in stock! I ordered: - Pan Au Chocolat - This thing is huge! Not much chocolate on the inside but the layers in this croissant are insane! They're thin, crispy, and so well defined. Never had a croissant this well done. Just wished there was more chocolate. - Morning Bun - Expected this to be light and fluffy but it was pretty hard. Again, I was quite impressed by the crispy layers, but the cinnamony spice blend was the real stand out here. Great flavor, not overly sweet, but just a bit too hard... - Jambon Royale & Gruyre - I didn't think I would ever pay $17 for a sandwich but I've heard such great things about Tartine that I had to try it. Tartine's bread is definitely the bakery's best item. I've tried it sliced and untoasted before and it was moist and fluffy with an incredible flavor. This time, the bread was grilled crisp with ham, cheese, and mustard in between and it did not disappoint. This sandwich was $17 but it's super filling and definitely shareable. Cheesy with a good portion of meat. It's a comforting classic sandwich. In conclusion, I would pick Tartine's bread over their pastries. Pastries were decent but didn't meet my expectations as well as their bread did.

You don't need me to tell you you should go to Tartine while in SF, do you? I was lucky enough to be staying nearby and so a friend and I wandered over on a Sunday morning. Around 9:00 am, the line wasn't too long and we were even able to snag two seats after ordering. Talk about a perfect morning! There's a paper menu which I would suggest grabbing because there's not much time for perusing once you hit the pastry counter. We ordered a croissant, quiche (there were two being offered - ham and potato, and sun dried tomato and kale), and morning bun. You can also order coffee at the register and it's prepared at the coffee bar for pickup. The croissant was bigger than I'm used to, in a great way. It was perfectly flaky and buttery. Just as it should be. The quiche was heated up before hitting our table and equally divine. I took the morning bun to go and enjoyed it the next day. It was so good! A little citrusy and a lot of sugary... Kind of like a cinnamon roll but without the icing. Regrets? I got 'em. Mainly that I didn't get a pastry to go. The lemon tart looked amazing! I also wish I would've ordered the bread pudding because another girl at our table was eating it so happily. I'm comforted by the fact I know I'll be back. I was always worried to come here because I knew the hype and feared the line wouldn't justify the means. Come early enough and you don't have to worry about that and let's be honest, even if you do, it's probably worth it.

By far one of my favorite bakeries in San Francisco. You will always find a wait here, but it's worth it!! Sourdough. I am on the hunt for the best sourdough in San Francisco. And so far, tartine is at the top of the list. I visited on Saturday morning and arrived a little after 10am. We stood in line for about 30 mins and took our pastries to go. We got the coconut macaroon, berry muffin, and plain croissant. On the menu, it said fresh baked breads are ready at ~3:30pm. I asked the waitress if they had sourdough and she asked if I wanted a full or half loaf. I was very excited that I'd be able to try out the sourdough bread. Plain croissant: wow, you can taste the butter. There were good flakes in the croissant, but definitely had better croissants from other SF bakeries. Coconut macaroon: yummy, it was crispy on the outside and soft on the inside. Berry muffin: it was ok. There was a layer of sugar on the top. The inside was moist, but not for me. Sourdough bread: STAR BAKERY ITEM! I'd wait in line again to get more of the bread. The crust was crispy and the inside was filled with holes and was so soft. Service was ok. Some waitresses seemed annoyed by the line of customers. There is seating inside (and tables get cleared as quickly as the line moves). Don't worry, there will be an open table by the time you get your food. You need to bus your own table. The bathroom is also clean.

Tartine is an awesome bakery and cafe. Everyone knows this and so there is a line out the door most times I visit. But their food is worth the wait. There is some Indoor and outdoor seating but Delores park is nearby so it always makes for a nice picnic too. They have amazing desserts, pastries, and sandwiches. Food wise they are perfection. The reason I am giving them 4 stars instead of 5 is that my last few visits the employees seem like they are sick of their customers. (Or at least that's what I've noticed). They seem annoyed that I wanted to order multiple items. An employee gave me unnecessary attitude for asking where to put the dishes and then told me i was doing it wrong when I hadn't even started yet. I simply put the plates down so I could organize my dishes since plates, silverware, cups, all have their own bins. I can imagine working at a busy cafe in sf can be stressful but no one wants to go to a cafe where the employees are grouchy. Regardless....I'll be back because the banana cream pie is literally heaven.

Protip: come on a weekday afternoon and there's no wait! But the baguettes are only ready after 2:30. Every time we're in the city, we can't help but stop by Tartine. This time we got the almond frangipane tart, lemon chiffon blueberry cake, buttermilk scone, and bread pudding. The almond tart was by far the heaviest, but still not too sweet. Everything was just sweet enough. My other favorites are the lemon meringue cake and lemon meringue tart. Hope to get them next time!

I've visited Tartine each and every time I have been to SF and it never disappoints. I've had their legendary Morning Bun, quiche, croissant, croque monsieur... its all delectable. The morning bun in particular is incredible: crisp, sweet but not too sweet, it leaves the most beautiful trace of orange in its aftertaste. The quiche also excellent, the egg mixture is soft and flavored with the ingredients of the day, held together by the perfectly crisp pasty. Croissants are sooo flakey too, I mean you can't go wrong. There is so much good food in SF, it's true, but Tartine deserves a spot and recognition among the best of the best.

Whenever we go here, the food service and music are always great I love the ambience and clean atmosphere. I'm always thrilled by the pastry cabinet. It's piled high with pies, tarts, cookies and cakes. You're going yummy yummy it makes you just drool and you are dreaming about the pie! Thanks Tartine for a wonderful time. The coffee is so good.

Do yourself a favor and get a phenomenal pastry! This bakery, said to be one of the best in the US, has a line out the door every time I'm there. They have a large assortment of pastries, croissants, cookies, desserts, etc to choose from. I had a very flavorful and flaky almond croissant. It was crispy on the outside and soft and gooey on the inside. With a side of coffee, your Sunday morning will be made! If you're in SF, go to Tartine!

    I almost missed this place since their signage is pretty much nonexistent on their storefront. Luckily, the line out the door let me know I arrived.

    Visited for the first time on Saturday around 4pm. Was worried that some of the pastries would be sold out but they still had everything I was eying in stock!

    I ordered:
    - Pan Au Chocolat - This thing is huge! Not much chocolate on the inside but the layers in this croissant are insane! They're thin, crispy, and so well defined. Never had a croissant this well done. Just wished there was more chocolate.
    - Morning Bun - Expected this to be light and fluffy but it was pretty hard. Again, I was quite impressed by the crispy layers, but the cinnamony spice blend was the real stand out here. Great flavor, not overly sweet, but just a bit too hard...
    - Jambon Royale & Gruyre - I didn't think I would ever pay $17 for a sandwich but I've heard such great things about Tartine that I had to try it. Tartine's bread is definitely the bakery's best item. I've tried it sliced and untoasted before and it was moist and fluffy with an incredible flavor. This time, the bread was grilled crisp with ham, cheese, and mustard in between and it did not disappoint. This sandwich was $17 but it's super filling and definitely shareable. Cheesy with a good portion of meat. It's a comforting classic sandwich.

    In conclusion, I would pick Tartine's bread over their pastries. Pastries were decent but didn't meet my expectations as well as their bread did.

    You don't need me to tell you you should go to Tartine while in SF, do you? I was lucky enough to be staying nearby and so a friend and I wandered over on a Sunday morning. Around 9:00 am, the line wasn't too long and we were even able to snag two seats after ordering. Talk about a perfect morning!

    There's a paper menu which I would suggest grabbing because there's not much time for perusing once you hit the pastry counter. We ordered a croissant, quiche (there were two being offered - ham and potato, and sun dried tomato and kale), and morning bun. You can also order coffee at the register and it's prepared at the coffee bar for pickup.

    The croissant was bigger than I'm used to, in a great way. It was perfectly flaky and buttery. Just as it should be. The quiche was heated up before hitting our table and equally divine. I took the morning bun to go and enjoyed it the next day. It was so good! A little citrusy and a lot of sugary... Kind of like a cinnamon roll but without the icing.

    Regrets? I got 'em. Mainly that I didn't get a pastry to go. The lemon tart looked amazing! I also wish I would've ordered the bread pudding because another girl at our table was eating it so happily. I'm comforted by the fact I know I'll be back.

    I was always worried to come here because I knew the hype and feared the line wouldn't justify the means. Come early enough and you don't have to worry about that and let's be honest, even if you do, it's probably worth it.

    Sourdough.

    I am on the hunt for the best sourdough in San Francisco. And so far, tartine is at the top of the list.

    I visited on Saturday morning and arrived a little after 10am. We stood in line for about 30 mins and took our pastries to go. We got the coconut macaroon, berry muffin, and plain croissant. On the menu, it said fresh baked breads are ready at ~3:30pm. I asked the waitress if they had sourdough and she asked if I wanted a full or half loaf. I was very excited that I'd be able to try out the sourdough bread.

    Plain croissant: wow, you can taste the butter. There were good flakes in the croissant, but definitely had better croissants from other SF bakeries.
    Coconut macaroon: yummy, it was crispy on the outside and soft on the inside.
    Berry muffin: it was ok. There was a layer of sugar on the top. The inside was moist, but not for me.
    Sourdough bread: STAR BAKERY ITEM! I'd wait in line again to get more of the bread. The crust was crispy and the inside was filled with holes and was so soft.

    Service was ok. Some waitresses seemed annoyed by the line of customers. There is seating inside (and tables get cleared as quickly as the line moves). Don't worry, there will be an open table by the time you get your food. You need to bus your own table. The bathroom is also clean.
